Trusted Computing Base: The VitaKernel, which is composed of these
Subsystems: VitaClip, VitaUI, VitaEdit, VitaFiles, VitaCrypt,
VitaCompress, VitaMount, VitaCompiler, VitaVM. 9 Subsystems, all in
Ring 0. All in one PE32+ file, signed for UEFI Secure Boot. The
VitaKernel is designed for the x86_64 Multicore Architecture. A future
port to another architecture would be when I can get my VitaFPGA
computer chips made, then I can make my VitaComputer.

To run an arbitrary program, compile and link the VitaKernel source
code and the program source code together using the VitaEdit program,
accessible from the VitaUI. This creates a VitaVM Image.

Then, sign the VitaVM Image with a VitaKernel Asymmetric Signing Key
using the VitaFiles program, accessible from the VitaUI.

Then, run it in a VitaVM with access to one or more directories in one
or more filesystems, using the VitaVM program, accessible from the
VitaUI.

To edit the Trusted Computing Base Source Code or arbitrary source
code, use the VitaEdit program, accessible from the VitaUI and press
the Save button from time to time.

To recompile the Trusted Computing Base Source Code or arbitrary source
code, with or without changes, use the VitaEdit program, accessible
from the VitaUI and press the VitaCompiler button.

To sign, verify, encrypt or decrypt files, directories and binaries
with a selected asymmetric key, use the VitaFiles program, accessible
from the VitaUI and press the VitaCrypt button. From there, follow the
pop-up instructions for signing, verifying, encrypting and decrypting
files, directories and binaries. You can import asymmetric keys and you
can create your own asymmetric keys.

To copy, delete, move, compress, decompress files, directories and
binaries and mount and unmount drives, use the VitaFiles program,
accessible from the VitaUI. Remember to make backups from time to time.

To interact with the VitaClip program, press Ctrl + C on selected text
to copy it into the clipboard, press Ctrl + V to paste from the
clipboard, answer “Yes” or “No” with the mouse or keyboard to let a
VitaVM read the clipboard, or press on the VitaClip program, accessible
from the VitaUI.

The VitaUI has a button that shows the choices of shutdown, reboot,
sleep and hibernate.

The VitaClip, VitaUI, VitaEdit, VitaFiles, VitaCrypt, VitaCompress,
VitaMount, VitaCompiler and VitaVM Subsystems run only on the Intel
Integrated Graphics. All of the Subsystems are multicore, but a VitaVM
can run with fewer cores. A VitaVM uses all cores by default.

The VitaVM shares PCIe PassThrough with the other Subsystems for the
Intel Integrated Graphics and the Laptop Ethernet Port.

The VitaOS-Libre Operating System will be optimized for my 2021 HP Omen
16.1” Gaming Laptop in Ceramic White with a 1440p display at 165 Hertz.
The VitaOS-Libre Operating System will not include the proprietary WiFi
Card Firmware, nor will it include the proprietary Nvidia Firmware.
I’ll only upgrade if I can get my own VitaFPGA computer chips made,
then I can make my VitaComputer.

A VitaVM Image can be an entire Operating System, not just a computer
program. While the VitaOS-Libre Operating System will not include the
proprietary WiFi Card Firmware, nor will it include the proprietary
Nvidia Firmware, a VitaVM can expose two PCIe Passthroughs so that you
can run a VitaVM Image that can access and use the Laptop Nvidia 3070
GPU and the Laptop WiFi Card in the 2021 HP Omen 16.1” Gaming Laptop in
Ceramic White with a 1440p display at 165 Hertz.
